Introduction to Open Data Science - Course Project

About the project

After completing this course you will understand the principles and advantages of using open research tools with open data and understand the possibilities of reproducible research. You will know how to use R, RStudio, RMarkdown, and GitHub for these tasks and also know how to learn more of these open software tools. You will also know how to apply certain statistical methods of data science, that is, data-driven statistics.

GitHub Repository: https://github.com/emilia-2022/IODS-project.git

# set working directory to access data

Explanations

This data set consists of information on 7 variables (X is merely an ID variable) collected on 166 students. Data was collected from 2014-2015 and the variables selected for this dataset focus on various ways of learning employed by students, their attitude towards statistics, as well as background information.

Below you can find a description of each variable present in the dataset:

Variable Name Type Descriptor
X Integer order of the variables (1-166)
Gender Character students gender, either M or F
Age Integer students age
Attitude Numeric (double) average of students attitude towards statistics
Deep Numeric (double) students use of deep learning
Strat Numeric (double) students use of strategic learning
Surf Numeric (double) students use of surface learning
Points Integer students exam score

Interpretations

From the graphical representation we can see their frequency, distributions, scatter plot, and correlations for each variable. Data from female students is shaded in pink and data from male students is shaded in light blue. Each variable will be interpreted in more detail below:

Gender

Frequency data reveals that the majority of respondents are female, with 110 respondents being female and 56 being male. There seems to be little correlation between gender and the other variables. Little is revealed from the scatter plots.

Age

Age is a variable which shows a highly skewed distribution with the majority of respondents being of a younger age. This is confirmed in the summary with the mean age being around 25 years old. Younger age seems to be characteristic irrespective of gender, although it seems that male respondents have a less sharp distribution curve.

Attitude

Attitude possess the highest statistically significant correlation with the variable points (representing exam scores). As the correlation is positive and significant (0.437) for both males and females we can interpret it as the more positive attitude one has towards statistics, the higher one will perform on exams. It seems that male students have a slightly more neutral/positive attitude towards statistics as exhibited in the distribution curve. Female students, having a less sharp distribution curve, are more neutral/neutral towards statistics with extreme opinions (points on the tails of the distribution curves) being infrequent, This is confirmed in the mean attitudes with males having a mean of 3.443 and females having a mean of 2.990.

Deep

Deep has the second highest statistically significant correlation, with males using surface learning. This is negative correlation meaning that males who do surface learning are less likely to do deep learning. This correlation is not significant for female students. Both genders have similar means for deep learning meaning that males are only slightly more likely to do deep learning than the other. As the means are higher than the other learning types (3.657 for females, 3.725 for males), it means that these students engage in deep learning more often than other types of learning.

Strat

Strategic learning is the second highest type of learning used: in both males and females (females mean 3.201, males 2.964). Contrasting deep learning, it appears that female students use strategic learning more than male students (as seen in the mean). No statistically significant correlations are present, but the highest correlation is with age. It is a positive correlation (0.102), meaning that those who are older use strategic learning more often.

Surf

Surface learning has the third highest statistically significant correlation with the variable attitude. Males are negatively correlated (-0.374) meaning that male students who do surface learning are more often have a negative attitude towards statistics. Compared to deep learning and strategic learning, students appear to use surface learning less (2.830 mean for females, 2.704 for males).

Model Building

Step 1: Initial Model

# create and fit regression model with three explanatory variables 
model <- lm(points ~ attitude + age + strat, data = students_learning2014)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + age + strat, data = students_learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -18.1149  -3.2003   0.3303   3.4129  10.7599 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 10.89543    2.64834   4.114 6.17e-05 ***
## attitude     3.48077    0.56220   6.191 4.72e-09 ***
## age         -0.08822    0.05302  -1.664   0.0981 .  
## strat        1.00371    0.53434   1.878   0.0621 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.26 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2182, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2037 
## F-statistic: 15.07 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 1.07e-08

Interpretations

From this model we can see that the combination of the three explanatory variables can explain up to 20.37% of the variation in a students exams scores. While all these variables are significant, only attitude is significant above the 99% threshold. Age and strategic learning are significant with a 90% confidence interval with the p-values 0.0981 and 0.0621 respectively.

From the coefficients we can see that for every increase in a positive attitude the students exam score will increase by 3.48077 points. For age, as it is negative coefficient, for each increase in age the exam points will decrease by -0.08822. Finally, for strategic learning, each increase in use will result in 1.00371 increase in exam points.

This models F-statistic has a low associated p-value at p= 1.07e-08.

Step 2: Re-Fitting the Model

model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = students_learning2014)
summary(model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = students_learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Interpretations

If we remove the explanatory variables that are significant below a 95% confidence threshold, we are left with the attitude variable. As seen in the lower adjusted R-squared value (0.1865), this model has lower predictive power than the previous model. Attitude can explain approximately 18% of the variation in ones exam scores. An increase in attitude still results in a slightly higher increase in exam points, 3.5255 compared to 3.48077, and the explanatory is still highly significant at p = 4.12e-09.

Step 3: Model Diagnostics

# place all four graphics in same plot
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
# draw diagnostic plots 
plot(model2, which = c(1,2,5))

Interpretations

From these diagnostics, it can be concluded that the final model is fairly appropriate. The residuals vs fitted plot shows enough randomness and does not appear to show and tunnel or curve patterns. The second plot, normal Q-Q, also confirms the models appropriateness as these is little departure from linearity. For the final plot, Residuals vs Leverage, it looks like no points are outside of Cooks distance meaning that none of the outliers possess enough leverage or influence to drastically change the model. However, the points 56 and 35 could be investigated more closely as they are close.

Explanations

Focusing on secondary students achievement at two schools in Portugal, this data set contains consisting of 35 variables with 370 observations. Originally, this data set consisted of two focusing on achievement in two subjects: math and Portuguese. These two sets were merged by the author and now contain combined information for each students achievement in each subject.

Information about these variables was collected using school reports and questionnaires the variables included are student grades, demographic, social and school related features. From the column names (seen above) it is clear that this data set covers these four aspects - with a special focus on social-related features. Variable types vary from integers, to numerical, character, and logical variables.

Additional attribute information can be found following: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance

Step 2: Hypotheses

Variable 1: Going Out

The first hypothesis to be examined is based on the variable going out with friends. Essentially, my hypothesis is that those who go out with their friends more often will be more prone to high alcohol use. I assume that drinking alcohol is a social bonding activity and this is why those who go out more frequently are more likely to have higher use.

Variable 2: Study Time

The second hypothesis is related to the variable study time. My hypothesis is that those who are studying more each week will have a lower chance of having high alcohol use. This hypothesis is purely based on my assumption that if you are spending the majority of your time studying, you will not have time to develop a high-use alcohol habit.

Variable 3: Health

The third hypothesis relates to the health variable. As it could potentially exacerbate existing poor health I hypothesize that those with poor health are less likely to have high alcohol use.

Variable 4: Sex

The final hypothesis focuses on the relationship between high alcohol use and sex. My hypothesis is that male students will have higher rates of alcohol use.

Interpretations

From the numerical summaries we can see that those with high-use alcohol consumption are more likely to be male, go out more and spend less time studying. We can also see from the first summary table that there are 259 students who are not high-use and 111 who are.

It appears that those who go out more often are more likely to have higher alcohol consumption. This is confirmed in previous summary table the higher means present in the going out (3.73 for True, 2.853 for False). These results are significant at a p-value of p = <0.001.

As for study time, the majority of those with high alcohol use study below 5 hours a week (42 for under 2 hours and 57 for under 5 hours). We can also see this in mean summary with a 1.77 average for those with high-use and a 2.16 average for those who do not have high-use. These results are significant at p= <0.001.

With a p value of p = 0.134, the only non-statistically significant results are those related to health. It can be observed that there is not a large difference between those who did not drink 3.5 and those who did 3.7. Perhaps then, in the context of this data set, ones health does not have a large effect on whether or not one drinks a lot.

Sex, as it is a character, was not covered in the first summary. However, in the second summary it can be observed that there males represent 63.1% of the high-use drinkers whereas females represent 36.9%. Rather intuitively these results are flipped with those who are not high-use. These results are significant at p= <0.001 which makes it significant at a 99% CI.

These results align with my hypothesis that students who spent more time studying are less probable to consume alcohol at high levels.

Interpretations

From this model we can see that three of the four explanatory variables are statistically significant. These three variables are significant at different confidence intervals however, and only going out is significant at the 99% threshold. The other two variables, study time and sex, are significant with a 95% confidence interval (p =3.03e-10 and a 90% CI (p =0.01073) respectively.

From the coefficients we can see that the effect of going out on high alcohol use is an increase in the risk for high-alcohol use with the more on goes out (0,75535). For study time, as it is negative coefficient, for each increase in time spent studying there will be a reduction in the risk for high alcohol use (-0.49173). As for health, there is no significant effect. Finally, for sex, if the sex is male it will result in a risk increase (0.67717).

Step 5: Predictive power

Using the variables which, according to your logistic regression model, had a statistical relationship with high/low alcohol consumption, explore the predictive power of you model.

Model Creation

final_model <- glm(high_use ~ goout + studytime + sex, data = alc_small, family = "binomial")

Provide a 2x2 cross tabulation of predictions versus the actual values and optionally display a graphic visualizing both the actual values and the predictions.

Cross tabulations: Predicted vs Actual

Numerical
# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(final_model, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc_small'
alc_small <- mutate(alc_small, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc_small <- mutate(alc_small, prediction = alc_small$probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions

Final Interpretations and Model/Hypotheses Comparison

A generous reading of the confusion matrix and the performance of the model would say that the model predicts false values correctly 9/10 of the time and positive values correctly 1/2 of the time. I do not believe that my simple guessing strategies would be able to reach this level of accuracy. When guessing, I often rely on broad generalizations (those who go out must drink more) to reach my conclusions. My hypotheses were thus oversimplified and did not reveal the nuance in the data. A clear example was that those who go out often have a 50% chance of having high alcohol use or not. Therefore, in order to reach the model accuracy, I would need to take more factors into account during my guessing. Yes, it is true that male students do drink more but is how much they drink proportionally to their weight taken into account? Therefore, while a simple guessing strategy can perhaps point the researcher which way to look, I do not think it can predict results as accurately as a well-built model can.
